With the assumption that _all_ functions in the call are of the same type, then it can be done with a simple generic type on the method:

    public static &lt;T&gt; T chain(
            T val,
            Function&lt;T, T&gt;... functions
    ) {
        if (functions.length == 0) return val;
        var nextInput = functions[0].apply(val);
        if (functions.length == 1) return nextInput;
        var tail = Arrays.copyOfRange(functions, 1, functions.length);
        return chain(nextInput, tail);
    }

There are other improvements that could be made (e.g. just using an index counter for the recursion to avoid array copies, or not being recursive). Be extra careful of boundary conditions, e.g. passing an empty call.

Using this, you may use any type for the input, and the functions will require operating on the same input and output types.

&gt; _&quot;Is it possible to recursively chain generic functions? ..._
&gt;
&gt; _... How can I make the method accept an arbitrary amount of functions? ...&quot;_

Your example will suffice, just utilize a _raw generic_; un-parameterized.

There&#39;s no reason to define a parameter if you&#39;re intending to use a _wildcard generic_ with _A_, _B_, _C_, and _D_.

_[Raw Types (The Java&amp;trade; Tutorials &amp;gt; Learning the Java Language &amp;gt; Generics (Updated))](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/rawTypes.html)_.

This will discourage a plausible overhead to the _functions_ array, and will provide fully restricted access to _val_ within _chain_.  

```java
@SuppressWarnings({&quot;rawtypes&quot;, &quot;unchecked&quot;})
public Object chain(Object val, Function ... functions) {
    Object nextInput = functions[0].apply(val);
    if (functions.length == 1) return nextInput;
    Function[] tail = Arrays.copyOfRange(functions, 1, functions.length);
    return chain(nextInput, tail);
}
```

